[1] Viet Nam: vaccination policy
Date: Wed 11 Jul 2007
From: Dung Do <dung.dah@gmail.com>


Re: PRO/AH/EDR> Avian influenza (126): Germany (Thuringia), Viet Nam
--------------------------------------------------------------------
Further to the question relating to vaccination in Viet Nam as
referred to in the ProMED-mail post below (archive No.
20070709.2185), I offer the following comments.

The only reason one would insist on using an antigen containing a
heterologous neuraminidase is if serological DIVA [differentiating
infected from vaccinated individuals] testing was being used.

At this point in the avian influenza (AI) control program in Viet Nam
the overall objective is to reduce the levels of infection, and
vaccination is one of the measures being used to achieve this. There
are some 8 million households rearing poultry in Viet Nam and it is
not possible to test all flocks of poultry before they go to market.
Therefore, routine DIVA testing is not an option (nor was routine
pre-market testing of poultry for infection possible before
vaccination was used -- and we know that some infected unprotected
flocks were sent to market by farmers).

The antigen in the vaccine used in Viet Nam (containing the HA and NA
from Goose/Guangdong/96) was chosen because it has been shown to
provide long lasting immunity against currently circulating viruses
and was a closer match to these viruses than the H5N2 antigen that
was used in chickens in Viet Nam in the 1st rounds of vaccination. It
also produces much better levels of protection in ducks than other
vaccines tested.

Over time, as the control program moves from one of containment to
one of elimination, it may be reasonable to switch to a vaccine that
allows for DIVA testing, provided the heterologous antigen still
affords the same level of protection as the current antigen, and DIVA
testing is demonstrated to be of benefit under Asian conditions with
HPAI (highly pathogenic avian influenza) viruses. (Readers may be
surprised to learn that there have been few if any formal field
studies on the use of DIVA testing in vaccinated flocks against H5N1
HPAI despite the widespread promotion of this method; DIVA studies so
far have been in flocks with LPAI (low pathogenic avian influenza) infections).

In addition, there are other means of detecting infection (which have
been used in Viet Nam and elsewhere) that provide information on
circulation of H5N1 viruses. These include investigations of
outbreaks of disease, testing of unvaccinated ducks, use of
sentinels, market testing for virus circulation, and testing of
routine dead birds in flocks. Serological DIVA testing is also
complicated in Asia by the circulation of other low pathogenicity AI
viruses. As a serological test, it also provides limited information
on the infection status of the flock at the time of sale; there is at
least a 17-day lag period between initial infection of a flock and
detection of infection through DIVA testing (7 days for the virus to
spread sufficiently in the flock and another 10 days for seroconversion).

Finally, some questions have been raised suggesting that the recent
cases of HPAI in ducks demonstrate that the vaccination campaign in
Viet Nam is not working. The vast majority of these cases has
occurred in unvaccinated ducks and show that this is not due to
failure of vaccination but rather failure to vaccinate. This issue of
non-vaccination is being addressed at present.

--
Do Huu Dung, DVM, MPhil.
Epidemiologist
Department of Animal Health,
15/78 Giai Phong Road
Phuong Mai, Dong Da, Hanoi
Viet Nam
<dung.dah@gmail.com>

[This is an authoritative, firsthand, clear, and most helpful update
on Viet Nam's vaccination programme. We are grateful to Dr Do Huu
Dung for the early and detailed response. We also wish to thank Marta
Martinez, a PhD student at the Faculty of Veterinary Science in
Madrid (UCM), who sent the query, which we posted in ProMED-mail
20070709.2185. - Mod.AS]

