[2] Viet Nam (Dien Bien, Ca Mau)
Date: Wed 11 Jul 2007
Source: ChinaView, Xinhua News Agency report [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-07/11/content_6361909.htm>


Bird flu has hit 2 more Vietnamese provinces, while several
localities nationwide have met criteria for announcing an end to bird
flu outbreaks in their territory, according to a local veterinary
agency on Wednesday [11 Jul 2007].

The disease, since [5 Jul 2007], killed about 500 ducks raised by 6
households in northern Dien Bien province's Dien Bien district, the
Department of Animal Health under the country's Ministry of
Agriculture and Rural Development said, noting that specimens from
the affected poultry have tested positive for the bird flu virus strain H5N1.

On [2 Jul 2007], bird flu was also found in a flock of 14 ducks
raised by a household in southern Ca Mau province's Dam Doi district,
with 9 ducks affected and 5 dead, said the department, adding that
the provincial veterinary bureau has slaughtered all fowls in the
affected flock.

Bird flu, which 1st struck Viet Nam in December 2003, has hit 20
Vietnamese cities and provinces since early May [2007].

To prevent the spread of the disease, the Vietnamese government has
called for more efforts in the fight against bird flu, mainly by
strengthening bird flu vaccination among poultry and tightening
management over poultry egg hatcheries.

So far this year [2007], the country has vaccinated 154.3 million
fowls, including 85.6 million chickens, 65.11 million ducks, and 3.59
million white-winged ducks, said the department.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[In another newswire submitted by ProMED-mail Rapportuer Mary
Marshall, more information on the outbreak in Dien Bien was provided:

"From [5-10 Jul 2007], the Dien Bien Veterinary Department detected 6
farmer families in 3 communes of Thanh Yen, Thanh Hung and Thanh
Xuong in Dien Bien District, had around 500 of the total 2400 ducks
died. All of the ducks are 25 days old and were not vaccinated
yet. The testing results show that they are positive to H5N1 virus.
The local Bird Flu Control Board on [10 Jul 2007] culled all fowl
flocks in the 2 communes of Thanh Xuong and Thanh Hung." (available
at <http://english.vietnamnet.vn/social/2007/07/717412/> - Mod.MPP]

[Dien Bien is a new province in Northern Viet Nam, which was created
by a split of the former Lai Chau Province. Ca Mau Province is
located at the southernmost extremity of the country. A map of Viet
Nam is available at <http://www.angelfire.com/co/hongnam/vnmap.html>.
- CopyEd.MJ]

******
[3] Czech Republic: poultry, 2 new outbreaks
Date: Thu 12 Jul 2007
Source: Reuters Foundation AlertNet [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L12545587.htm>


Czechs confirm H5N1 bird flu at 2 more farms
--------------------------------------------
Tests confirmed the H5N1 type of the bird flu virus in poultry at 2
farms in the eastern Czech Republic, the State Veterinary Authority
(SVS) said on Thursday [12 Jul 2007]. The virus was found at the 2
farms with 71 000 poultry, bringing the number of outbreaks in Czech
farms to 4.

Vets were preparing to cull all birds on the farms on Thursday [12
Jul 2007], spokesman Josef Duben said. "It was H5N1, we had expected
that and taken standard protective measures," he added.

The Czechs identified their 1st bird flu case, which involved the
lethal H5N1 strain, at a turkey farm in the eastern part of the
country in June [2007].

The 2 farms where disease was reported on Wednesday [11 Jul 2007],
are within a 3-km (1.9-mi) protective zone around another farm where
H5N1 had been found. Vets have extended the standard 3-km protection
zone and 10-km 96.2 mi) surveillance zone to include the 2 farms.

More than 30 countries have reported bird flu outbreaks in the past
year, mostly in wild birds.

Since late June [2007], Germany has reported the H5N1 virus in dozens
of wild birds and in a pet goose.

Globally, H5N1 has killed nearly 200 people out of more than 300
known cases, according to the World Health Organisation. None of the
victims were from Europe.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

